===Etymology 1===
[[Image:Tiled roof in Dubrovnik-edit.jpg|thumb]]
{{ja-kanjitab|かわら|yomi=kun}}
{{IPAchar|/kapara/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaɸara/}} → {{IPAchar|/kawara/}}

From {{etyl|sa|ja|sort=かわら}} {{m|sa|कपाल||[[w:kapala|kapala]]|pos="[[pot]]", "[[skull]]", etc.}}<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>, via {{etyl|ltc|ja|sort=かわら}} {{m|ltc|迦波羅|tr=kˠa puɑ lɑ}}.  Along with Buddhism, roof tiles came to Japan in the [[w:Asuka period|Asuka period]], once found on Buddhist temples. Later on, the trend of roof tiles spread throughout medieval Japan.

Folk etymologies exist:
# From the belief that said tiles were made of clay, {{ja-r|土|つち}}, and like pottery they were fired, as in "changed": {{ja-r|変わる|かわる}}, therefore ''kawara'' was derived from its [[未然形#Japanese|imperfective form]], {{ja-r|変わら|かわら}} {{rfv-etymology|ja}}. 
# From [[万葉仮名#Japanese|man'yōgana]] {{ja-r|伽%和%羅|か%わ%ら|[[甲冑#Japanese|helmet and armor]]}}, or {{ja-r|加%宇%良|か%う%ら|[[tortoise]] [[shell]]}}, both relating to armor {{rfv-etymology|ja}}.

